{{Infobox medical condition (new) | name = Crush injury | synonyms = | image = | alt = | caption = | pronounce = | field = | symptoms = | complications = | onset = | duration = | types = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = | deaths = }} A '''crush injury''' is [[trauma (medicine)|injury]] by an object that causes [[Compression (physics)|compression]] of the [[Human body|body]].<ref name="britannica">{{Citation|year=2010|title=crush injury|place=Chicago|publisher =[[Encyclopædia Britannica]]|url=https://www.britannica.com/science/crush-injury}}</ref><ref name="rosen">{{cite book |author1=Ron Walls MD |author2=John J. Ratey MD |author3=Robert I. Simon MD |title=Rosen's Emergency Medicine: Expert Consult Premium Edition - Enhanced Online Features and Print (Rosen's Emergency Medicine: Concepts & Clinical Practice (2v.)) |publisher=Mosby |location=St. Louis |year=2009 |pages=2482–3 |isbn=0-323-05472-2}}</ref> This form of injury is common following a [[natural disaster]] or after some form of trauma from a deliberate [[Assault|attack]].<ref name="extra">{{cite journal | url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.injury.2011.06.368 | title=Crush injuries and crush syndrome—A review |author1=N.A. Jagodzinski |author2=C. Weerasinghe |author3=K. Porter | journal=Injury Extra |date=July 2011 | volume=42 | issue=9 | pages=154–5 | doi=10.1016/j.injury.2011.06.368}}</ref> Common concerns after an injury of this type are [[rhabdomyolysis]] and [[crush syndrome]].<ref name="extra"/>
